# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: disk-forensics-sleuthkit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Although it is most often associated with the investigation of a wide variety of computer crime, computer forensics may also be used in civil proceedings.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] The discipline involves similar techniques and principles to data recovery, but with additional guidelines and practices designed to create a legal audit trail.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Evidence from computer forensics investigations is usually subjected to the same guidelines and practices as other digital evidence.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] It has been used in a number of high-profile cases and is accepted as reliable within U.S. and European court systems.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] In the early 1980s, personal computers became more accessible to consumers, leading to their increased use in criminal activity (for example, to help commit fraud).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] At the same time, several new "computer crimes" were recognized (such as cracking).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] The discipline of computer forensics emerged during this time as a method to recover and investigate digital evidence for use in court.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Since then, computer crime and computer-related crime has grown, with the FBI reporting a suspected 791,790 internet crimes in 2020, a 69% increase over the amount reported in 2019.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Today, computer forensics is used to investigate a wide variety of crimes, including child pornography, fraud, espionage, cyberstalking, murder, and rape.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] The discipline also features in civil proceedings as a form of information gathering (e.g., Electronic discovery).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Forensic techniques and expert knowledge are used to explain the current state of a *digital artifact*, such as a computer system, storage medium (e.g., hard disk or CD-ROM), or an electronic document (e.g., an email message or JPEG image).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] The scope of a forensic analysis can vary from simple information retrieval to reconstructing a series of events.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] In a 2002 book, *Computer Forensics*, authors Kruse and Heiser define computer forensics as involving "the preservation, identification, extraction, documentation and interpretation of computer data".
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] They describe the discipline as "more of an art than a science," indicating that forensic methodology is backed by flexibility and extensive domain knowledge.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] However, while several methods can be used to extract evidence from a given computer, the strategies used by law enforcement are fairly rigid and lack the flexibility found in the civilian world.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Computer forensics is often confused with cybersecurity.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Cybersecurity focuses on prevention and protection, while computer forensics is more reactionary and active, involving activities such as tracking and exposing.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] System security usually encompasses two teams: cybersecurity and computer forensics, which work together.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] A cybersecurity team creates systems and programs to protect data; if these fail, the computer forensics team recovers the data and investigates the intrusion and theft.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Both areas require knowledge of computer science.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Computer forensics are used to convict those involved in physical and digital crimes.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Some of these computer-related crimes include interruption, interception, copyright infringement, and fabrication.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] *Interruption* relates to the destruction and stealing of computer parts and digital files.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] *Interception* is the unauthorized access of files and information stored on technological devices.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Copyright infringement refers to using, reproducing, and distributing copyrighted information, including software piracy.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] *Fabrication* involves accusing someone of using false data and information inserted into the system through an unauthorized source.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Examples of interceptions include the Bank NSP case, Sony.Sambandh.com case, and business email compromise scams.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] In court, computer forensic evidence is subject to the usual requirements for digital evidence.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] This requires that information be authentic, reliably obtained, and admissible.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Different countries have specific guidelines and practices for evidence recovery.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] In the United Kingdom, examiners often follow Association of Chief Police Officers guidelines that help ensure the authenticity and integrity of evidence.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] While voluntary, the guidelines are widely accepted in British courts.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Computer forensics has been used as evidence in criminal law since the mid-1980s.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Computer forensic investigations typically follow the standard digital forensic process, consisting of four phases: acquisition, examination, analysis, and reporting.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Investigations are usually performed on static data (i.e., acquired images) rather than "live" systems.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] This differs from early forensic practices, when a lack of specialized tools often required investigators to work on live data.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] The computer forensics lab is a secure environment where electronic data can be preserved, managed, and accessed under controlled conditions, minimizing the risk of damage or alteration to the evidence.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Forensic examiners are provided with the resources necessary to extract meaningful data from the devices they examine.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] where encryption keys can be retrieved, or for imaging the logical hard drive volume (a live acquisition) before shutting down the computer.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Live analysis is also beneficial when examining networked systems or cloud-based devices that cannot be accessed physically.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] A common forensic technique involves recovering deleted files.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Forensic software can "carve" files by searching for known file headers and reconstructing deleted data.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Steganography involves concealing data within another file, such as hiding illegal content within an image.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Forensic investigators detect steganography by comparing file hashes, as any hidden data will alter the hash value of the file.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Phone companies typically retain logs of received calls, which can help create timelines and establish suspects' locations at the time of a crime.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] are useful in narrowing down suspects based on their connections to the victim.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Text messages contain timestamps and remain in company servers, often indefinitely, even if deleted from the device.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] These records are valuable evidence for reconstructing communication between individuals.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Photos can provide critical evidence, supporting or disproving alibis by showing the location and time they were taken.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Some victims may have recorded pivotal moments, capturing details like the attacker's voice, which could provide crucial evidence.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Volatile data is stored in memory or in transit and is lost when the computer is powered down.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] It resides in locations such as registries, cache, and RAM.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] When seizing evidence, if a machine is still active, volatile data stored solely in RAM may be lost if not recovered before shutting down the system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] "Live analysis" can be used to recover RAM data (e.g., using Microsoft's COFEE tool, WinDD, WindowsSCOPE) before removing the machine.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Tools like CaptureGUARD Gateway allow for the acquisition of physical memory from a locked computer.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] RAM data can sometimes be recovered after power loss, as the electrical charge in memory cells dissipates slowly.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Techniques like the cold boot attack exploit this property.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Lower temperatures and higher voltages increase the chance of recovery, but it is often impractical to implement these techniques in field investigations.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Tools that extract volatile data often require the computer to be in a forensic lab to maintain the chain of evidence.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] In some cases, a live desktop can be transported using tools like a mouse jiggler to prevent sleep mode and an uninterruptible power supply (UPS) to maintain power.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Page files from file systems with journaling features, such as NTFS and ReiserFS, can also be reassembled to recover RAM data stored during system operation.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Numerous open-source and commercial tools exist for computer forensics.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Common forensic analysis includes manual reviews of media, Windows registry analysis, password cracking, keyword searches, and the extraction of emails and images.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Tools such as Autopsy (software), Belkasoft Evidence Center X, Forensic Toolkit (FTK), and EnCase are widely used in digital forensics.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] A digital forensics analyst is responsible for preserving digital evidence, cataloging collected evidence, analyzing evidence relevant to the ongoing case, responding to cyber breaches (often in a corporate context), writing reports containing findings, and testifying in court.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] A digital forensic analyst may also be referred to as a computer forensic analyst, digital forensic examiner, cyber forensic analyst, forensic technician, or other similarly named titles, though these roles perform similar duties.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Several computer forensics certifications are available, such as the ISFCE Certified Computer Examiner, Digital Forensics Investigation Professional (DFIP), and IACRB Certified Computer Forensics Examiner.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] The top vendor-independent certification, particularly within the EU, is the Certified Cyber Forensics Professional (CCFP).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/computer-forensics] Many commercial forensic software companies also offer proprietary certifications.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] A **disk image** is a snapshot of a storage device's content – typically stored in a file on another storage device.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Traditionally, a disk image was relatively large because it was a bit-by-bit copy of every storage location of a device (i.e. every sector of a hard disk drive), but it is now common to only store allocated data to reduce storage space.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Compression and deduplication are commonly used to further reduce the size of image files.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Disk imaging is performed for a variety of purposes including digital forensics, cloud computing, system administration, backup, and emulation for digital preservation strategy.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Despite the benefits, storage costs can be high, management can be difficult and imaging can be time consuming.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Disk images can be made in a variety of formats depending on the purpose.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Virtual disk images (such as VHD and VMDK) are intended to be used for cloud computing, ISO images are intended to emulate optical media, such as a CD-ROM.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Raw disk images are used for forensic purposes.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Proprietary formats are typically used by disk imaging software.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Disk images were originally (in the late 1960s) used for backup and disk cloning of mainframe disk media.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Early ones were as small as 5 megabytes and as large as 330 megabytes, and the copy medium was magnetic tape, which ran as large as 200 megabytes per reel.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Disk images became much more popular when floppy disk media became popular, where replication or storage of an exact structure was necessary and efficient, especially in the case of copy protected floppy disks.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Disk image creation is called disk imaging and is often time consuming, even with a fast computer, because the entire disk must be copied.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Typically, disk imaging requires a third party disk imaging program or backup software.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] The software required varies according to the type of disk image that needs to be created.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] For example, RawWrite and WinImage create floppy disk image files for MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] In Unix or similar systems the dd program can be used to create raw disk images.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Apple Disk Copy can be used on Classic Mac OS and macOS systems to create and write disk image files.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Authoring software for CDs/DVDs such as Nero Burning ROM can generate and load disk images for optical media.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] A *virtual disk writer* or *virtual burner* is a computer program that emulates an actual disc authoring device such as a CD writer or DVD writer.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Instead of writing data to an actual disc, it creates a virtual disk image.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] A virtual burner, by definition, appears as a disc drive in the system with writing capabilities (as opposed to conventional disc authoring programs that can create virtual disk images), thus allowing software that can burn discs to create virtual discs.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Forensic imaging is the process of creating a bit-by-bit copy of the data on the drive, including files, metadata, volume information, filesystems and their structure.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Often, these images are also hashed to verify their integrity and that they have not been altered since being created.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Unlike disk imaging for other purposes, digital forensic applications take a bit-by-bit copy to ensure forensic soundness.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] The purposes of imaging the disk is to not only discover evidence preserved in digital information but also to examine the drive to gather clues of how the crime was committed.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Creating a virtual disk image of optical media or a hard disk drive is typically done to make the content available to one or more virtual machines.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Virtual machines emulate a CD/DVD drive by reading an ISO image.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] This can also be faster than reading from the physical optical medium.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Further, there are less issues with wear and tear.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] A hard disk drive or solid-state drive in a virtual machine is implemented as a disk image (i.e. either the VHD format used by Microsoft's Hyper-V, the VDI format used by Oracle Corporation's VirtualBox, the VMDK format used for VMware virtual machines, or the QCOW format used by QEMU).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Virtual hard disk images tend to be stored as either a collection of files (where each one is typically 2GB in size), or as a single file.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Virtual machines treat the image set as a physical drive.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Educational institutions and businesses can often need to buy or replace computer systems in large numbers.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Disk imaging is commonly used to rapidly deploy the same configuration across workstations.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Disk imaging software is used to create an image of a completely-configured system (such an image is sometimes called a golden image).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] This image is then written to a computer's hard disk (which is sometimes described as restoring an image).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Image restoration can be done using network-based image deployment.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] This method uses a PXE server to boot an operating system over a computer network that contains the necessary components to image or restore storage media in a computer.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] This is usually used in conjunction with a DHCP server to automate the configuration of network parameters including IP addresses.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Multicasting, broadcasting or unicasting tend to be used to restore an image to many computers simultaneously.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] These approaches do not work well if one or more computers experience packet loss.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] As a result, some imaging solutions use the BitTorrent protocol to overcome this problem.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Network-based image deployment reduces the need to maintain and update individual systems manually.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Imaging is also easier than automated setup methods because an administrator does not need to have knowledge of the prior configuration to copy it.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] A disk image contains all files and data (i.e., file attributes and the file fragmentation state).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] For this reason, it is also used for backing up optical media (CDs and DVDs, etc.), and allows the exact and efficient recovery after experimenting with modifications to a system or virtual machine.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Typically, disk imaging can be used to quickly restore an entire system to an operational state after a disaster.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Libraries and museums are typically required to archive and digitally preserve information without altering it in any manner.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Emulators frequently use disk images to emulate floppy disks that have been preserved.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] This is usually simpler to program than accessing a real floppy drive (particularly if the disks are in a format not supported by the host operating system), and allows a large library of software to be managed.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Emulation also allows existing disk images to be put into a usable form even though the data contained in the image is no longer readable without emulation.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Disk imaging is time consuming, the space requirements are high and reading from them can be slower than reading from the disk directly because of a performance overhead.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Other limitations can be the lack of access to software required to read the contents of the image.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] For example, prior to Windows 8, third party software was required to mount disk images.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] When imaging multiple computers with only minor differences, much data is duplicated unnecessarily, wasting space.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Disk imaging can be slow, especially for older storage devices.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] A typical 4.7 GB DVD can take an average of 18 minutes to duplicate.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Floppy disks read and write much slower than hard disks.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Therefore, despite their small size, it can take several minutes to copy a single disk.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] In some cases, disk imaging can fail due to bad sectors or physical wear and tear on the source device.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] Unix utilities (such as dd) are not designed to cope with failures, causing the disk image creation process to fail.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/disk-image] When data recovery is the end goal, it is instead recommended to use more specialised tools (such as ddrescue).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] It is used in IT forensics and data recovery.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Carving is typically used on storage media with a corrupted file system or for storage areas that are listed as free in the existing file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] All filesystems contain some metadata that describes the actual file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] At a minimum, this includes the hierarchy of folders and files, with names for each.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] The filesystem will also record the physical locations on the storage device where each file is stored.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] As explained below, a file might be scattered in fragments at different physical addresses.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] File carving is the process of trying to recover files without this metadata.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] This is done by analyzing the raw data and identifying what it is (text, executable, png, mp3, etc.).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] This can be done in different ways, but the simplest is to look for the file signature or "magic numbers" that mark the beginning and/or end of a particular file type.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] For instance, every Java class file has as its first four bytes the hexadecimal value `CA FE BA BE`.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Some files contain footers as well, making it just as simple to identify the ending of the file.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Most file systems, such as the FAT family and UNIX's Fast File System, work with the concept of clusters of an equal and fixed size.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] For example, a FAT32 file system might be broken into clusters of 4 KiB each.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Any file smaller than 4 KiB fits into a single cluster, and there is never more than one file in each cluster.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Files that take up more than 4 KiB are allocated across many clusters.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Sometimes these clusters are all contiguous, while other times they are scattered across two or potentially many more so called fragments, with each fragment containing a number of contiguous clusters storing one part of the file's data.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Obviously, large files are more likely to be fragmented.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Simson Garfinkel reported fragmentation statistics collected from over 350 disks containing FAT, NTFS and UFS file systems.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] He showed that while fragmentation in a typical disk is low, the fragmentation rate of forensically important files such as email, JPEG and Word documents is relatively high.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] The fragmentation rate of JPEG files was found to be 16%, Word documents had 17% fragmentation, AVI had a 22% fragmentation rate and PST files (Microsoft Outlook) had a 58% fragmentation rate (the fraction of files being fragmented into two or more fragments).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Pal, Shanmugasundaram, and Memon presented an efficient algorithm based on a greedy heuristic and alpha-beta pruning for reassembling fragmented images.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Pal, Sencar, and Memon introduced sequential hypothesis testing as an effective mechanism for detecting fragmentation points.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Richard and Roussev presented Scalpel, an open-source file-carving tool existing since 2005 and initially based on Foremost.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] File carving is a highly complex task, with a potentially huge number of permutations to try.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] To make this task tractable, carving software typically makes extensive use of models and heuristics.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] This is necessary not only from a standpoint of execution time, but also for the accuracy of the results.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] State-of-the-art file carving algorithms use statistical techniques like sequential hypothesis testing for determining fragmentation points.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] In most cases, when a file is deleted, the entry in the file system metadata is removed but the actual data is still on the disk.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] File carving can be used to recover data from a hard disk where the metadata was removed or otherwise damaged.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] This process may be successful even after a drive is formatted or repartitioned.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] File carving can be performed using free or commercial software and is often performed in conjunction with computer forensics examinations or alongside other recovery efforts (e.g. hardware repair) by data recovery companies.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Whereas the primary goal of data recovery is to recover the file content, computer forensics examiners are often just as interested in the metadata such as who owned a file, where it was stored, and when it was last modified.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Thus, while a forensic examiner could use file carving to prove that a file was once stored on a hard drive, he or she might need to seek out other evidence to prove who put it there.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Garfinkel introduced the use of fast object validation for reassembling files that have been split into two pieces.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] This technique is referred to as Bifragment Gap Carving (BGC).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] A set of starting fragments and a set of finishing fragments are identified.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] The fragments are reassembled if together they form a valid object.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Pal developed a carving scheme that is not limited to bifragmented files.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] The technique, known as SmartCarving, makes use of heuristics regarding the fragmentation behavior of known filesystems.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] The algorithm has three phases: preprocessing, collation, and reassembly.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] In the preprocessing phase, blocks are decompressed and/or decrypted if necessary.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] In the collation phase, blocks are sorted according to their file type.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] In the reassembly phase, the blocks are placed in sequence to reproduce the deleted files.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] The SmartCarving algorithm is the basis for the Adroit Photo Forensics and Adroit Photo Recovery applications from Digital Assembly.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Snapshots of computers' volatile memory (i.e.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Memory-dump carving is routinely used in digital forensics, allowing investigators to access ephemeral evidence.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] Ephemeral evidence includes recently accessed images and Web pages, documents, chats and communications committed via social networks.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] For example, LiME can be used in conjunction with Volatility to do such a task.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] If an encrypted volume (TrueCrypt, BitLocker, PGP Disk) was used, binary keys to encrypted containers can be extracted and used to instantly mount such volumes.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] The content of volatile memory gets fragmented.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-carving] A proprietary carving algorithm was developed by Belkasoft to enable carving fragmented memory sets (BelkaCarving).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] In computing, a **file system** or **filesystem** (often abbreviated to **FS** or **fs**) governs file organization and access.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A *local* file system is a capability of an operating system that services the applications running on the same computer.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A *distributed* file system is a protocol that provides file access between networked computers.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A file system provides a data storage service that allows applications to share mass storage.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Without a file system, applications could access the storage in incompatible ways that lead to resource contention, data corruption, and data loss.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] There are many file system designs and implementations – with various structures and features and various resulting characteristics such as speed, flexibility, security, size, and more.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] File systems have been developed for many types of storage devices, including hard disk drives (HDDs), solid-state drives (SSDs), magnetic tapes and optical discs.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A portion of the computer main memory can be set up as a RAM disk that serves as a storage device for a file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] File systems such as tmpfs can store files in virtual memory.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A *virtual* file system provides access to files that are either computed on request, called *virtual files* (for example those provided by procfs and sysfs), or are mapping into another, backing storage.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] 1900 and before the advent of computers, the terms *file system*, *filing system* and *system for filing* were used to describe methods of organizing, storing and retrieving paper documents.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] By 1961, the term *file system* was being applied to computerized filing alongside the original meaning.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A local file system's architecture can be described as layers of abstraction even though a particular file system design may not actually separate the concepts.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The *logical file system* layer provides relatively high-level access via an application programming interface (API) for file operations including open, close, read and write – delegating operations to lower layers.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] This layer manages open file table entries and per-process file descriptors.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] It provides file access, directory operations, security, and protection.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The *virtual file system*, an optional layer, supports multiple concurrent instances of physical file systems, each of which is called a file system implementation.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The *physical file system* layer provides relatively low-level access to a storage device (e.g. disk).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] It reads and writes data blocks, provides buffering and other memory management, and controls placement of blocks in specific locations on the storage medium.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] This layer uses device drivers or channel I/O to drive the storage device.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A *file name*, or *filename*, identifies a file to consuming applications and in some cases users.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A file name is unique so that an application can refer to exactly one file for a particular name.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] If the file system supports directories, then generally file name uniqueness is enforced within the context of each directory.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] In other words, a storage can contain multiple files with the same name, but not in the same directory.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Most file systems restrict the length of a file name.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some file systems match file names as case sensitive and others as case insensitive.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] For example, the names `MYFILE` and `myfile` match the same file for case-insensitive, but different files for case-sensitive.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Most modern file systems allow a file name to contain a wide range of characters from the Unicode character set.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some restrict characters such as those used to indicate special attributes such as a device, device type, directory prefix, file path separator, or file type.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] File systems typically support organizing files into *directories*, also called *folders*, which segregate files into groups.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] This may be implemented by associating the file name with an index in a table of contents or an inode in a Unix-like file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Directory structures may be flat (i.e. linear), or allow hierarchies by allowing a directory to contain directories, called subdirectories.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The first file system to support arbitrary hierarchies of directories was used in the Multics operating system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A file system stores associated metadata separate from the content of the file.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Most file systems store the names of all the files in one directory in one place—the directory table for that directory—which is often stored like any other file.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Many file systems put only some of the metadata for a file in the directory table, and the rest of the metadata for that file in a completely separate structure, such as the inode.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Most file systems also store metadata not associated with any one particular file.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Such metadata includes information about unused regions—free space bitmap, block availability map—and information about bad sectors.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Often such information about an allocation group is stored inside the allocation group itself.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Additional attributes can be associated on file systems, such as NTFS, XFS, ext2, ext3, some versions of UFS, and HFS+, using extended file attributes.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some file systems provide for user defined attributes such as the author of the document, the character encoding of a document or the size of an image.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some file systems allow for different data collections to be associated with one file name.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] These separate collections may be referred to as *streams* or *forks*.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Apple has long used a forked file system on the Macintosh, and Microsoft supports streams in NTFS.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some file systems maintain multiple past revisions of a file under a single file name; the file name by itself retrieves the most recent version, while prior saved versions can be accessed using a special naming convention such as "filename;4" or "filename(-4)" to access the version four saves ago.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A local file system tracks which areas of storage belong to which file and which are not being used.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] When a file system creates a file, it allocates space for data.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some file systems permit or require specifying an initial space allocation and subsequent incremental allocations as the file grows.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] To delete a file, the file system records that the file's space is free (available to use for another file).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A local file system manages storage space to provide a level of reliability and efficiency.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Generally, it allocates storage device space in a granular manner, usually multiple physical units (i.e. bytes).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] For example, in Apple DOS of the early 1980s, 256-byte sectors on 140 kilobyte floppy disk used a *track/sector map*.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The granular nature results in unused space, sometimes called slack space, for each file except for those that have the rare size that is a multiple of the granular allocation.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] For a 512-byte allocation, the average unused space is 256 bytes.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] For 64 KB clusters, the average unused space is 32 KB.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Generally, the allocation unit size is set when the storage is configured.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Choosing a relatively small size compared to the files stored results in excessive access overhead.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Choosing a relatively large size results in excessive unused space.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Choosing an allocation size based on the average size of files expected to be in the storage tends to minimize unusable space.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] As a file system creates, modifies, and deletes files, the underlying storage representation may become fragmented.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Files and the unused space between files will occupy allocation blocks that are not contiguous.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A file becomes fragmented if space needed to store its content cannot be allocated in contiguous blocks.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Free space becomes fragmented when files are deleted.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Fragmentation is invisible to the end user and the system still works correctly.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] However, this can degrade performance on some storage hardware that works better with contiguous blocks such as hard disk drives.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Other hardware such as solid-state drives are not affected by fragmentation.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A file system often supports access control of data that it manages.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The intent of access control is often to prevent certain users from reading or modifying certain files.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Access control can also restrict access by program to ensure that data is modified in a controlled way.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Examples include passwords stored in the metadata of the file or elsewhere and file permissions in the form of permission bits, access control lists, or capabilities.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The need for file system utilities to be able to access the data at the media level to reorganize the structures and provide efficient backup usually means that these are only effective for polite users, but are not effective against intruders.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Methods for encrypting file data are sometimes included in the file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] This is very effective since there is no need for file system utilities to know the encryption seed to effectively manage the data.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The risks of relying on encryption include the fact that an attacker can copy the data and use brute force to decrypt the data.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Additionally, losing the seed means losing the data.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some operating systems allow a system administrator to enable disk quotas to limit a user's use of storage space.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Recovery from exceptional situations may include updating metadata, directory entries, and handling data that was buffered but not written to storage media.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Many file systems access data as a stream of bytes.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Typically, to read file data, a program provides a memory buffer and the file system retrieves data from the medium and then writes the data to the buffer.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A write involves the program providing a buffer of bytes that the file system reads and then stores to the medium.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some file systems, or layers on top of a file system, allow a program to define a record so that a program can read and write data as a structure, not an unorganized sequence of bytes.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] If a *fixed length* record definition is used, then locating the nth record can be calculated mathematically, which is relatively fast compared to parsing the data for record separators.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] An identification for each record, also known as a key, allows a program to read, write, and update records without regard to their location in storage.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Such storage requires managing blocks of media, usually separating key blocks and data blocks.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Efficient algorithms can be developed with pyramid structures for locating records.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Typically, a file system can be managed by the user via various utility programs.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some utilities allow the user to create, configure and remove an instance of a file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] It may allow extending or truncating the space allocated to the file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Directory utilities may be used to create, rename, and delete *directory entries*, which are also known as *dentries* (singular: *dentry*), and to alter metadata associated with a directory.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Directory utilities may also include capabilities to create additional links to a directory (hard links in Unix), to rename parent links (".." in Unix-like operating systems), and to create bidirectional links to files.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] File utilities create, list, copy, move, and delete files, and alter metadata.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] They may be able to truncate data, truncate or extend space allocation, append to, move, and modify files in-place.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Depending on the underlying structure of the file system, they may provide a mechanism to prepend to or truncate from the beginning of a file, insert entries into the middle of a file, or delete entries from a file.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Utilities to free space for deleted files, if the file system provides an undelete function, also belong to this category.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some file systems defer operations such as reorganization of free space, secure erasing of free space, and rebuilding of hierarchical structures by providing utilities to perform these functions at times of minimal activity.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] An example is the file system defragmentation utilities.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some of the most important features of file system utilities are supervisory activities, which may involve bypassing ownership or direct access to the underlying device.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] These include high-performance backup and recovery, data replication, and reorganization of various data structures and allocation tables within the file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Utilities, libraries, and programs use file system APIs to make requests of the file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] These include data transfer, positioning, updating metadata, managing directories, managing access specifications, and removal.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Frequently, retail systems are configured with a single file system occupying the entire storage device.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Another approach is to partition the disk so that several file systems with different attributes can be used.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] One file system, for use as browser cache or email storage, might be configured with a small allocation size.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] This keeps the activity of creating and deleting files typical of browser activity in a narrow area of the disk where it will not interfere with other file allocations.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Another partition might be created for the storage of audio or video files with a relatively large block size.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Yet another may normally be set *read-only* and only periodically be set writable.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some file systems, such as ZFS and APFS, support multiple file systems sharing a common pool of free blocks, supporting several file systems with different attributes without having to reserve a fixed amount of space for each file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A third approach, which is mostly used in cloud systems, is to use "disk images" to house additional file systems, with the same attributes or not, within another (host) file system as a file.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A common example is virtualization: one user can run an experimental Linux distribution (using the ext4 file system) in a virtual machine under their production Windows environment (using NTFS).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The ext4 file system resides in a disk image, which is treated as a file (or multiple files, depending on the hypervisor and settings) in the NTFS host file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Having multiple file systems on a single system has the additional benefit that in the event of a corruption of a single file system, the remaining file systems will frequently still be intact.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] This includes virus destruction of the *system* file system or even a system that will not boot.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] File system utilities that require dedicated access can be effectively completed piecemeal.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] In addition, defragmentation may be more effective.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Several system maintenance utilities, such as virus scans and backups, can also be processed in segments.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] For example, it is not necessary to backup the file system containing videos along with all the other files if none have been added since the last backup.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] As for the image files, one can easily "spin off" differential images that contain only "new" data written to the master (original) image.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A *disk file system* takes advantage of the ability of disk storage media to randomly address data in a short amount of time.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Additional considerations include the speed of accessing data following that initially requested and the anticipation that the following data may also be requested.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] This permits multiple users (or processes) access to various data on the disk without regard to the sequential location of the data.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Examples include FAT (FAT12, FAT16, FAT32), exFAT, NTFS, ReFS, HFS and HFS+, HPFS, APFS, UFS, ext2, ext3, ext4, XFS, btrfs, Files-11, Veritas File System, VMFS, ZFS, ReiserFS, NSS and ScoutFS.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some disk file systems are journaling file systems or versioning file systems.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] ISO 9660 and Universal Disk Format (UDF) are two common formats that target Compact Discs, DVDs and Blu-ray discs.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Mount Rainier is an extension to UDF supported since 2.6 series of the Linux kernel and since Windows Vista that facilitates rewriting to DVDs.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A *flash file system* considers the special abilities, performance and restrictions of flash memory devices.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Frequently a disk file system can use a flash memory device as the underlying storage media, but it is much better to use a file system specifically designed for a flash device.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A *tape file system* is a file system and tape format designed to store files on tape.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Magnetic tapes are sequential storage media with significantly longer random data access times than disks, posing challenges to the creation and efficient management of a general-purpose file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] In a disk file system there is typically a master file directory, and a map of used and free data regions.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Any file additions, changes, or removals require updating the directory and the used/free maps.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Random access to data regions is measured in milliseconds so this system works well for disks.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Tape requires linear motion to wind and unwind potentially very long reels of media.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] This tape motion may take several seconds to several minutes to move the read/write head from one end of the tape to the other.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Consequently, a master file directory and usage map can be extremely slow and inefficient with tape.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Writing typically involves reading the block usage map to find free blocks for writing, updating the usage map and directory to add the data, and then advancing the tape to write the data in the correct spot.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Each additional file write requires updating the map and directory and writing the data, which may take several seconds to occur for each file.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Tape file systems instead typically allow for the file directory to be spread across the tape intermixed with the data, referred to as *streaming*, so that time-consuming and repeated tape motions are not required to write new data.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] However, a side effect of this design is that reading the file directory of a tape usually requires scanning the entire tape to read all the scattered directory entries.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Most data archiving software that works with tape storage will store a local copy of the tape catalog on a disk file system, so that adding files to a tape can be done quickly without having to rescan the tape media.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The local tape catalog copy is usually discarded if not used for a specified period of time, at which point the tape must be re-scanned if it is to be used in the future.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] IBM has developed a file system for tape called the Linear Tape File System.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The IBM implementation of this file system has been released as the open-source IBM Linear Tape File System — Single Drive Edition (LTFS-SDE) product.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The Linear Tape File System uses a separate partition on the tape to record the index meta-data, thereby avoiding the problems associated with scattering directory entries across the entire tape.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Writing data to a tape, erasing, or formatting a tape is often a significantly time-consuming process and can take several hours on large tapes.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] With many data tape technologies it is not necessary to format the tape before over-writing new data to the tape.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] This is due to the inherently destructive nature of overwriting data on sequential media.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Because of the time it can take to format a tape, typically tapes are pre-formatted so that the tape user does not need to spend time preparing each new tape for use.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] All that is usually necessary is to write an identifying media label to the tape before use, and even this can be automatically written by software when a new tape is used for the first time.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] In the 1970s disk and digital tape devices were too expensive for some early microcomputer users.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] An inexpensive basic data storage system was devised that used common audio cassette tape.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] When the system needed to write data, the user was notified to press "RECORD" on the cassette recorder, then press "RETURN" on the keyboard to notify the system that the cassette recorder was recording.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The system wrote a sound to provide time synchronization, then modulated sounds that encoded a prefix, the data, a checksum and a suffix.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] When the system needed to read data, the user was instructed to press "PLAY" on the cassette recorder.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The system would *listen* to the sounds on the tape waiting until a burst of sound could be recognized as the synchronization.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The system would then interpret subsequent sounds as data.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] When the data read was complete, the system would notify the user to press "STOP" on the cassette recorder.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] It was primitive, but it (mostly) worked.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Data was stored sequentially, usually in an unnamed format, although some systems (such as the Commodore PET series of computers) did allow the files to be named.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Multiple sets of data could be written and located by fast-forwarding the tape and observing at the tape counter to find the approximate start of the next data region on the tape.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The user might have to listen to the sounds to find the right spot to begin playing the next data region.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some implementations even included audible sounds interspersed with the data.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Another concept for file management is the idea of a database-based file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Instead of, or in addition to, hierarchical structured management, files are identified by their characteristics, like type of file, topic, author, or similar rich metadata.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Soltis IBM's former chief scientist for IBM i.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Soltis and his team at IBM Rochester had successfully designed and applied technologies like the database file system where others like Microsoft later failed to accomplish.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] These technologies are informally known as 'Fortress Rochester' and were in few basic aspects extended from early Mainframe technologies but in many ways more advanced from a technological perspective.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some programs need to either make multiple file system changes, or, if one or more of the changes fail for any reason, make none of the changes.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] For example, a program which is installing or updating software may write executables, libraries, and/or configuration files.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] If some of the writing fails and the software is left partially installed or updated, the software may be broken or unusable.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] An incomplete update of a key system utility, such as the command shell, may leave the entire system in an unusable state.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Transaction processing introduces the atomicity guarantee, ensuring that operations inside of a transaction are either all committed or the transaction can be aborted and the system discards all of its partial results.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] This means that if there is a crash or power failure, after recovery, the stored state will be consistent.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Either the software will be completely installed or the failed installation will be completely rolled back, but an unusable partial install will not be left on the system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Transactions also provide the isolation guarantee, meaning that operations within a transaction are hidden from other threads on the system until the transaction commits, and that interfering operations on the system will be properly serialized with the transaction.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Windows, beginning with Vista, added transaction support to NTFS, in a feature called Transactional NTFS, but its use is now discouraged.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] There are a number of research prototypes of transactional file systems for UNIX systems, including the Valor file system, Amino, LFS, and a transactional ext3 file system on the TxOS kernel, as well as transactional file systems targeting embedded systems, such as TFFS.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Ensuring consistency across multiple file system operations is difficult, if not impossible, without file system transactions.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] File locking can be used as a concurrency control mechanism for individual files, but it typically does not protect the directory structure or file metadata.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] For instance, file locking cannot prevent TOCTTOU race conditions on symbolic links.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] File locking also cannot automatically roll back a failed operation, such as a software upgrade; this requires atomicity.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Journaling file systems is one technique used to introduce transaction-level consistency to file system structures.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Journal transactions are not exposed to programs as part of the OS API; they are only used internally to ensure consistency at the granularity of a single system call.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Data backup systems typically do not provide support for direct backup of data stored in a transactional manner, which makes the recovery of reliable and consistent data sets difficult.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Most backup software simply notes what files have changed since a certain time, regardless of the transactional state shared across multiple files in the overall dataset.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] As a workaround, some database systems simply produce an archived state file containing all data up to that point, and the backup software only backs that up and does not interact directly with the active transactional databases at all.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Recovery requires separate recreation of the database from the state file after the file has been restored by the backup software.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A *network file system* is a file system that acts as a client for a remote file access protocol, providing access to files on a server.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Programs using local interfaces can transparently create, manage and access hierarchical directories and files in remote network-connected computers.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Examples of network file systems include clients for the NFS, AFS, SMB protocols, and file-system-like clients for FTP and WebDAV.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A *shared disk file system* is one in which a number of machines (usually servers) all have access to the same external disk subsystem (usually a storage area network).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The file system arbitrates access to that subsystem, preventing write collisions.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Examples include GFS2 from Red Hat, GPFS, now known as Spectrum Scale, from IBM, SFS from DataPlow, CXFS from SGI, StorNext from Quantum Corporation and ScoutFS from Versity.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some file systems expose elements of the operating system as files so they can be acted on via the file system API.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] This is common in Unix-like operating systems, and to a lesser extent in other operating systems.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] In a flat file system, there are no subdirectories; files are stored on a disk without hierarchy.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] While simple, this become awkward as the number of files grows and makes it difficult to organize files into related groups.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The mainframe DOS/360 and OS/360 store entries for all files on a disk pack (*volume*) in a directory on the pack called a *Volume Table of Contents* (VTOC).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Some minicomputer operating systems, such as RT-11, had a flat file system with only one top-level directory.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Others, such as RSX-11, supported a top-level directory and subdirectories for user accounts, but did not support subdirectories of the user-account directories.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Most 8-bit microcomputer operating systems originally used flat file systems (e.g., Apple DOS, Atari DOS).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] CP/M machines use a flat file system, where files can be assigned to one of 16 *user areas* and generic file operations narrowed to work on one instead of defaulting to work on all of them.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] These user areas are no more than special attributes associated with the files; it is not necessary to define specific quota for each of these areas and files can be added to groups for as long as there is free storage space on the disk.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The FAT file system in IBM PC DOS/MS-DOS was a flat file system until DOS version 2.0, when support for subdirectories was added.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The classic Mac OS for the Macintosh supported only the flat Macintosh File System until the Hierarchical File System was introduced in version 2.1.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The file management program, the Finder, created the illusion of a partially hierarchical filing system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] This structure required every file to have a unique name, even if it appeared to be in a separate folder.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A 21st century addition to the flat file system family is Amazon's S3, a remote storage service, which is intentionally simplistic to allow users the ability to customize how their data is stored.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The only constructs are buckets (imagine a disk drive of unlimited size) and objects (similar, but not identical to the standard concept of a file).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Advanced file management is allowed by being able to use nearly any character (including '/') in the object's name, and the ability to select subsets of the bucket's content based on identical prefixes.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] In computing, a hierarchical file system is a file system that uses directories to organize files into a tree structure.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] In a hierarchical file system, *directories* contain information about both files and other directories, called *subdirectories* which, in turn, can point to other subdirectories, and so on.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] This is organized as a tree structure, or *hierarchy*, generally portrayed with the root at the top.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] The *root directory* is the base of the hierarchy, and is usually stored at some fixed location on disk.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] A hierarchical file system contrasts with a *flat file system*, where information about all files is stored in a single directory, and there are no subdirectories.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] Almost all file systems today are hierarchical.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] What is referred to as a file system is a specific instance of a hierarchical system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p01] For example, NTFS, HPFS, and ext4, all implement a hierarchical system with different features for buffering, file allocation, and file recovery.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] An operating system (OS) typically supports one or more file systems.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Sometimes an OS and its file system are so tightly interwoven that it is difficult to describe them independently.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] An OS typically provides file system access to the user.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Often an OS provides a command line interface, such as a Unix shell, Windows Command Prompt and PowerShell, or OpenVMS DCL.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] An OS often also provides a file browser in a graphical user interface such as Finder on macOS, File Explorer on Windows, GNOME Files in GNOME, or Dolphin in KDE Plasma.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Unix-like operating systems create a virtual file system, which makes all files on all connected storage devices appear to exist in a single hierarchy.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] This means, in those systems, there is one root directory, and every file existing on the system is located under it somewhere.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Unix-like systems can use a RAM disk or network shared resource as its root directory.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Unix-like systems assign a device name to each device, but this is not how the files on that device are accessed.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Instead, to gain access to files on another device, the operating system must first be informed where in the directory tree those files should appear.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] This process is called mounting a file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] For example, to access the files on a CD-ROM, one must tell the operating system "Take the file system from this CD-ROM and make it appear under such-and-such directory." The directory given to the operating system is called the *mount point* – it might, for example, be /media.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The /media directory exists on many Unix systems (as specified in the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard) and is intended specifically for use as a mount point for removable media such as CDs, DVDs, USB drives or floppy disks.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] It may be empty, or it may contain subdirectories for mounting individual devices.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Generally, only the administrator (i.e. root user) may authorize the mounting of file systems.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Unix-like operating systems often include software and tools that assist in the mounting process and provide it new functionality.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Some of these strategies have been coined "auto-mounting" as a reflection of their purpose.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Linux supports numerous file systems, but common choices for the system disk on a block device include the ext* family (ext2, ext3 and ext4), XFS, JFS, and btrfs.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] For raw flash without a flash translation layer (FTL) or Memory Technology Device (MTD), there are UBIFS, JFFS2 and YAFFS, among others.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] SquashFS is a common compressed read-only file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Solaris in earlier releases defaulted to (non-journaled or non-logging) UFS for bootable and supplementary file systems.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Solaris defaulted to, supported, and extended UFS.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Support for other file systems and significant enhancements were added over time, including Veritas Software Corp.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] (journaling) VxFS, Sun Microsystems (clustering) QFS, Sun Microsystems (journaling) UFS, and Sun Microsystems (open source, poolable, 128 bit compressible, and error-correcting) ZFS.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Kernel extensions were added to Solaris to allow for bootable Veritas VxFS operation.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Logging or journaling was added to UFS in Sun's Solaris 7.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Releases of Solaris 10, Solaris Express, OpenSolaris, and other open source variants of the Solaris operating system later supported bootable ZFS.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Logical Volume Management allows for spanning a file system across multiple devices for the purpose of adding redundancy, capacity, and/or throughput.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Legacy environments in Solaris may use Solaris Volume Manager (formerly known as Solstice DiskSuite).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Multiple operating systems (including Solaris) may use Veritas Volume Manager.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Modern Solaris based operating systems eclipse the need for volume management through leveraging virtual storage pools in ZFS.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] macOS (formerly Mac OS X) uses the Apple File System (APFS), which in 2017 replaced a file system inherited from classic Mac OS called HFS Plus (HFS+).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Apple also uses the term "Mac OS Extended" for HFS+.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] HFS Plus is a metadata-rich and case-preserving but (usually) case-insensitive file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Due to the Unix roots of macOS, Unix permissions were added to HFS Plus.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Later versions of HFS Plus added journaling to prevent corruption of the file system structure and introduced a number of optimizations to the allocation algorithms in an attempt to defragment files automatically without requiring an external defragmenter.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] HFS Plus uses Unicode to store file names.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] On macOS, the filetype can come from the type code, stored in file's metadata, or the filename extension.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] HFS Plus has three kinds of links: Unix-style hard links, Unix-style symbolic links, and aliases.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Aliases are designed to maintain a link to their original file even if they are moved or renamed; they are not interpreted by the file system itself, but by the File Manager code in userland.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] macOS 10.13 High Sierra, which was announced on June 5, 2017, at Apple's WWDC event, uses the Apple File System on solid-state drives.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] macOS also supported the UFS file system, derived from the BSD Unix Fast File System via NeXTSTEP.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] However, as of Mac OS X Leopard, macOS could no longer be installed on a UFS volume, nor can a pre-Leopard system installed on a UFS volume be upgraded to Leopard.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] As of Mac OS X Lion UFS support was completely dropped.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Newer versions of macOS are capable of reading and writing to the legacy FAT file systems (16 and 32) common on Windows.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] They are also capable of *reading* the newer NTFS file systems for Windows.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] In order to *write* to NTFS file systems on macOS versions prior to Mac OS X Snow Leopard third-party software is necessary.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Mac OS X 10.6 (Snow Leopard) and later allow writing to NTFS file systems, but only after a non-trivial system setting change (third-party software exists that automates this).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Finally, macOS supports reading and writing of the exFAT file system since Mac OS X Snow Leopard, starting from version 10.6.5.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] OS/2 1.2 introduced the High Performance File System (HPFS).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] A journaled filesystem (JFS) was shipped in 1999.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] PC-BSD is a desktop version of FreeBSD, which inherits FreeBSD's ZFS support, similarly to FreeNAS.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The new graphical installer of PC-BSD can handle */ (root) on ZFS* and RAID-Z pool installs and disk encryption using Geli right from the start in an easy convenient (GUI) way.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The current PC-BSD 9.0+ 'Isotope Edition' has ZFS filesystem version 5 and ZFS storage pool version 28.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Plan 9 from Bell Labs treats everything as a file and accesses all objects as a file would be accessed (i.e., there is no ioctl or mmap): networking, graphics, debugging, authentication, capabilities, encryption, and other services are accessed via I/O operations on file descriptors.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The 9P protocol removes the difference between local and remote files.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] File systems in Plan 9 are organized with the help of private, per-process namespaces, allowing each process to have a different view of the many file systems that provide resources in a distributed system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The Inferno operating system shares these concepts with Plan 9.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Windows makes use of the FAT, NTFS, exFAT, Live File System and ReFS file systems (the last of these is only supported and usable in Windows Server 2012, Windows Server 2016, Windows 8, Windows 8.1, and Windows 10; Windows cannot boot from it).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Windows uses a *drive letter* abstraction at the user level to distinguish one disk or partition from another.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] For example, the path C:\WINDOWS represents a directory WINDOWS on the partition represented by the letter C.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Drive C: is most commonly used for the primary hard disk drive partition, on which Windows is usually installed and from which it boots.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] This "tradition" has become so firmly ingrained that bugs exist in many applications which make assumptions that the drive that the operating system is installed on is C.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The use of drive letters, and the tradition of using "C" as the drive letter for the primary hard disk drive partition, can be traced to MS-DOS, where the letters A and B were reserved for up to two floppy disk drives.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] This in turn derived from CP/M in the 1970s, and ultimately from IBM's CP/CMS of 1967.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The family of FAT file systems is supported by almost all operating systems for personal computers, including all versions of Windows and MS-DOS/PC DOS, OS/2, and DR-DOS.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] (PC DOS is an OEM version of MS-DOS, MS-DOS was originally based on SCP's 86-DOS.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] DR-DOS was based on Digital Research's Concurrent DOS, a successor of CP/M-86.) The FAT file systems are therefore well-suited as a universal exchange format between computers and devices of most any type and age.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The FAT file system traces its roots back to an (incompatible) 8-bit FAT precursor in Standalone Disk BASIC and the short-lived MDOS/MIDAS project.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Over the years, the file system has been expanded from FAT12 to FAT16 and FAT32.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Various features have been added to the file system including subdirectories, codepage support, extended attributes, and long filenames.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Third parties such as Digital Research have incorporated optional support for deletion tracking, and volume/directory/file-based multi-user security schemes to support file and directory passwords and permissions such as read/write/execute/delete access rights.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Most of these extensions are not supported by Windows.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The FAT12 and FAT16 file systems had a limit on the number of entries in the root directory of the file system and had restrictions on the maximum size of FAT-formatted disks or partitions.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] FAT32 addresses the limitations in FAT12 and FAT16, except for the file size limit of close to 4 GB, but it remains limited compared to NTFS.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] FAT12, FAT16 and FAT32 also have a limit of eight characters for the file name, and three characters for the extension (such as .exe).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] This is commonly referred to as the 8.3 filename limit.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] VFAT, an optional extension to FAT12, FAT16 and FAT32, introduced in Windows 95 and Windows NT 3.5, allowed long file names (LFN) to be stored in the FAT file system in a backwards compatible fashion.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] NTFS, introduced with the Windows NT operating system in 1993, allowed ACL-based permission control.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Other features also supported by NTFS include hard links, multiple file streams, attribute indexing, quota tracking, sparse files, encryption, compression, and reparse points (directories working as mount-points for other file systems, symlinks, junctions, remote storage links).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] exFAT has certain advantages over NTFS with regard to file system overhead.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] exFAT is not backward compatible with FAT file systems such as FAT12, FAT16 or FAT32.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The file system is supported with newer Windows systems, such as Windows XP, Windows Server 2003, Windows Vista, Windows 2008, Windows 7, Windows 8, Windows 8.1, Windows 10 and Windows 11.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] exFAT is supported in macOS starting with version 10.6.5 (Snow Leopard).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Support in other operating systems is sparse since implementing support for exFAT requires a license. exFAT is the only file system that is fully supported on both macOS and Windows that can hold files larger than 4 GB.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Files-11 is the file system used in the RSX-11, IAS, and OpenVMS operating systems from Digital Equipment Corporation.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] It supports record-oriented I/O, remote network access, and file versioning.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The original ODS-1 layer is a flat file system; the ODS-2 version is a hierarchical file system, with support for access control lists.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Files-11 is similar to, but significantly more advanced than, the file systems used in previous Digital Equipment Corporation operating systems such as TOPS-20 and RSTS/E.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Prior to the introduction of VSAM, OS/360 systems implemented a hybrid file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The system was designed to easily support removable disk packs, so the information relating to all files on one disk (*volume* in IBM terminology) is stored on that disk in a flat system file called the *Volume Table of Contents* (VTOC).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The VTOC stores all metadata for the file.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Later a hierarchical directory structure was imposed with the introduction of the *System Catalog*, which can optionally catalog files (datasets) on resident and removable volumes.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The catalog only contains information to relate a dataset to a specific volume.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] If the user requests access to a dataset on an offline volume, and they have suitable privileges, the system will attempt to mount the required volume.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Cataloged and non-cataloged datasets can still be accessed using information in the VTOC, bypassing the catalog, if the required volume id is provided to the OPEN request.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Still later the VTOC was indexed to speed up access.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The IBM Conversational Monitor System (CMS) component of VM/370 uses a separate flat file system for each virtual disk (*minidisk*).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] File data and control information are scattered and intermixed.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The anchor is a record called the *Master File Directory* (MFD), always located in the fourth block on the disk.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Originally CMS used fixed-length 800-byte blocks, but later versions used larger size blocks up to 4K.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Access to a data record requires two levels of indirection, where the file's directory entry (called a *File Status Table* (FST) entry) points to blocks containing a list of addresses of the individual records.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Data on the AS/400 and its successors consists of system objects mapped into the system virtual address space in a single-level store.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Many types of objects are defined including the directories and files found in other file systems.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] File objects, along with other types of objects, form the basis of the AS/400's support for an integrated relational database.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] File systems limit storable data capacity – generally driven by the typical size of storage devices at the time the file system is designed and anticipated into the foreseeable future.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Since storage sizes have increased at near exponential rate (see Moore's law), newer storage devices often exceed existing file system limits within only a few years after introduction.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] This requires new file systems with ever increasing capacity.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] With higher capacity, the need for capabilities and therefore complexity increases as well.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] File system complexity typically varies proportionally with available storage capacity.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Capacity issues aside, the file systems of early 1980s home computers with 50 KB to 512 KB of storage would not be a reasonable choice for modern storage systems with hundreds of gigabytes of capacity.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Likewise, modern file systems would not be a reasonable choice for these early systems, since the complexity of modern file system structures would quickly consume the limited capacity of early storage systems.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] It may be advantageous or necessary to have files in a different file system than they currently exist.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Reasons include the need for an increase in the space requirements beyond the limits of the current file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The depth of path may need to be increased beyond the restrictions of the file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] There may be performance or reliability considerations.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Providing access to another operating system which does not support the existing file system is another reason.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] In some cases conversion can be done in-place, although migrating the file system is more conservative, as it involves a creating a copy of the data and is recommended.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] On Windows, FAT and FAT32 file systems can be converted to NTFS via the convert.exe utility, but not the reverse.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] On Linux, ext2 can be converted to ext3 (and converted back), and ext3 can be converted to ext4 (but not back), and both ext3 and ext4 can be converted to btrfs, and converted back until the undo information is deleted.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] These conversions are possible due to using the same format for the file data itself, and relocating the metadata into empty space, in some cases using sparse file support.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Migration has the disadvantage of requiring additional space although it may be faster.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] The best case is if there is unused space on media which will contain the final file system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] For example, to migrate a FAT32 file system to an ext2 file system, a new ext2 file system is created.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Then the data from the FAT32 file system is copied to the ext2 one, and the old file system is deleted.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] An alternative, when there is not sufficient space to retain the original file system until the new one is created, is to use a work area (such as a removable media).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] This takes longer but has the benefit of producing a backup.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] In hierarchical file systems, files are accessed by means of a *path* that is a branching list of directories containing the file.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Different file systems have different limits on the depth of the path.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] File systems also have a limit on the length of an individual file name.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] Copying files with long names or located in paths of significant depth from one file system to another may cause undesirable results.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/file-system-p02] This depends on how the utility doing the copying handles the discrepancy.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/the-sleuth-kit] The software is under active development and it is supported by a team of developers.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/the-sleuth-kit] The initial development was done by Brian Carrier who based it on The Coroner's Toolkit.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/the-sleuth-kit] The Sleuth Kit is capable of parsing NTFS, FAT, ExFAT, UFS versions 1 and 2, Ext2, Ext3, Ext4, HFS, ISO 9660 and YAFFS2 file systems either on disk or within whole disk or disk partition images stored in raw form (as can be obtained with dd), or Expert Witness or AFF formats.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/the-sleuth-kit] The Sleuth Kit can be used to examine the contents of most computers that run Microsoft Windows, macOS, or Linux and some other computers which run derivatives of Unix such as the BSDs or Solaris.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/the-sleuth-kit] The Sleuth Kit can be used via the included command line tools, or as a library embedded within a separate digital forensic tool such as Autopsy or log2timeline/plaso.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] A **forensic disk controller** or **hardware write-block device** is a specialized type of computer hard disk controller made for the purpose of gaining read-only access to computer hard drives without the risk of damaging the drive's contents.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] The device is named forensic because its most common application is for use in investigations where a computer hard drive may contain evidence.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] Such a controller historically has been made in the form of a dongle that fits between a computer and an IDE or SCSI hard drive, but with the advent of USB and SATA, forensic disk controllers supporting these newer technologies have become widespread.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] Steve Bress and Mark Menz invented hard drive write blocking (US Patent 6,813,682).
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] A device which is installed between a storage media under investigation and an investigator's computer is called a "**bridge kit**".
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] The bridge kit has one connector for the storage media and another connector the investigator's computer.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] It allows the investigator to read, but not alter the device under investigation.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] Forensic disk controllers intercept write commands from the host operating system, preventing them from reaching the drive.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] Whenever the host bus architecture supports it the controller reports that the drive is read-only.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] The disk controller can either deny all writes to the disk and report them as failures, or use on-board memory to cache the writes for the duration of the session.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] A disk controller that caches writes in memory presents the appearance to the operating system that the drive is writable, and uses the memory to ensure that the operating system sees changes to the individual disk sectors it attempted to overwrite.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] It does this by retrieving sectors from the disk if the operating system hasn't attempted to change them, and retrieving the changed version from memory for sectors that have been changed.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] Forensic disk controllers are most commonly associated with the process of creating a disk image, or acquisition, during forensic analysis.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] Their use is to prevent inadvertent modification of evidence.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] Using hardware to protect the hard drive from writes is very important for several reasons.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] First, many operating systems, including Windows, may write to any hard disk that is connected to the system.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] At the very least, Windows will update the access time for any file accessed, and may write things to the disk unexpectedly - such as creating hidden folders for the recycle bin or saved hardware configuration.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] Virus infections or malware on the system used for analysis may attempt to infect the disk being inspected.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] Additionally, the NTFS file system may attempt to commit or rollback unfinished transactions, and/or change flags on the volume to mark it as "in use".
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] At the worst, undesired files may allocate and overwrite deleted space on the hard disk which may potentially destroy evidence in the form of previously deleted files.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] Protecting an evidence drive from writes during investigation is also important to counter potential allegations that the contents of the drive were altered during the investigation.
[src:disk-forensics-sleuthkit/write-blocker] Of course, this can be alleged anyway, but in the absence of technology to protect a drive from writes, there is no way for such an allegation to be refuted.
